title: Three.js: Constructors should be declared with "new".
body:
In the interfaces I changed, there were the following problems: 
- The constructor (static) part of the interface, was a function, but not declared with new. Meaning that the declaration said one should do: `THREE.WebGLObjects()` to get an WebGLObjects instance. But that returns undefined, since one is supposed to call `new THREE.WebGLObjects()`. 
- The instance part of the interface for some reason had a constructor. Which is simply untrue, since they are not even a function.

title: Enable LF normalization
body:
Per git's documentation, the previous configuration (`text=none`) is equivalent to leaving `text` unspecified, which isn't useful.  `text=auto` means that all line endings are normalized to LF in the repository and will be checked out as LF on Mac & Linux, CRLF on Windows.  I think this makes more sense to avoid patches like #7823 where entire files are affected just because line endings were different.

https://www.kernel.org/pub/software/scm/git/docs/gitattributes.html#_tt_text_tt

title: bluebird: fixed inference issue with try/attempt
body:
The source of the issue is described here:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/35182445/unsure-why-casting-is-required-in-this-typescript-code-my-derp-or-language-lim

I ran into a type inference issue with try/attempt (possibly a tsc bug/limitation) that is fixed by having the type definitions use a union type rather than two overloads with different return types.

I added two test cases for each try and attempt on both versions of bluebird.

The first test case demonstrates that tsc can't correctly infer the generic parameter for try/accept if we use overloads, and without this fix you get the following error:

```
bluebird/bluebird-1.0-tests.ts(511,1): error TS2322: Type 'Promise<Foo | Promise<Foo>>' is not assignable to type 'Promise<Foo>'.
    Type 'Foo | Promise<Foo>' is not assignable to type 'Foo'.
        Type 'Promise<Foo>' is not assignable to type 'Foo'.
        Property 'foo' is missing in type 'Promise<Foo>'.
```

The second test case demonstrates that even if you tell it the generic parameter the type inference doesn't pick up on the fact that () => T|Promise<T> would satisfy one overload or the other.  Without this fix you would get the following error:

```
bluebird/bluebird-1.0-tests.ts(514,28): error TS2345: Argument of type '() => Foo | Promise<Foo>' is not assignable to parameter of type '() => Foo'.
    Type 'Foo | Promise<Foo>' is not assignable to type 'Foo'.
    Type 'Promise<Foo>' is not assignable to type 'Foo'.
```

The fix to the type definitions is to use a union return type, which causes both tests to pass and better reflects the intent of the bluebird js api.

title: Rename the type variable for es6-promise from R to T to match lib.d.ts.
body:
This fixes an issue where two definitions for Promise that /should/ agree
(i.e., be assignable to one another) aren't, and instead the immensely
confusing error message:

```
error TS2314: Generic type 'Promise<T, R>' requires 2 type argument(s).
```

Even though all the present definitions are paramaterized with a single type
variable, Typescript appears to assume that the two different names are
referring to two different types and therefore you must supply both. Here I
changed it to T from R so that it matches lib.d.ts.

For reference, this error occured for me specifically when I had both
es6-promise and bluebird typings present. bluebird uses T already.
